tad , in this very manner, after receiving from both of us the sum of three dīnāras, in order to increase the merit of the both of us, be so kind as to give to the venerable Arhants of the monastery in the same Vaṭa-Gohālī, overseen by the grand-disciple of the disciple of the Jaina śramaṇa master Guhanandin of the Kāśika-Pañcastūpa school,
I see the part of the compound ° nigrantha-śramaṇācāryya-guhanandi-śiṣya-praśiṣyādhiṣṭhita° in line 6 as a kind of guru-lineage whose function would be to proove the great age of this monastery or to assert the high standing of its leader. Consequently I translate both śiṣya and praśiṣya by a singular. for the sake of perfume, incense, flowers and lamps, etc., , and for the purpose of use as an adjacent park, one-and-a-half kulyavāpa of land as permanent endowment divided exactly as it follows:
